04402nam a22006495i 9781442684195DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172006onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426841957 a10.3138/97814426841952doi  a(DE-B1597)483056  a(OCoLC)1004875989  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aSOC0220002bisacsh04a792.097135411 aMcKinnie, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCity Stages :bTheatre and Urban Space in a Global City /cMichael McKinnie. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2017] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCultural Spaces00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNomenclature -- tIntroduction: Towards an Urban Analysis of Theatre in Toronto -- tPART ONE. Civic Development -- t1. Urban National, Suburban Transnational: Civic Theatres and the Urban Development of Toronto’s Downtowns -- t2. Good Times, Inc.: Constructing a Civic Play Economy in the Entertainment District -- tPART TWO. The Edifice Complex -- t3. Space Administration: Locating an Urban History of Theatre Passe Muraille -- t4. A Troubled Home: Spatializing the Demise of Toronto Workshop Productions -- t5. Movin’ On Up: Spatial Scarcity, Cultural Equity, and the Geography of Theatrical Legitimacy -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn every major city, there exists a complex exchange between urban space and the institution of the theatre. City Stages is an interdisciplinary and materialist analysis of this relationship as it has existed in Toronto since 1967. Locating theatre companies – their sites and practices – in Toronto’s urban environment, Michael McKinnie focuses on the ways in which the theatre has adapted to changes in civic ideology, environment, and economy. Over the past four decades, theatre in Toronto has been increasingly implicated in the civic self-fashioning of the city and preoccupied with the consequences of the changing urban political economy. City Stages investigates a number of key questions that relate to this pattern. How has theatre been used to justify certain forms of urban development in Toronto? How have local real estate markets influenced the ways in which theatre companies acquire and use performance space? How does the analysis of theatre as an urban phenomenon complicate Canadian theatre historiography? McKinnie uses the St. Lawrence Centre for the Arts and the Toronto Centre for the Performing Arts as case studies and considers theatrical companies such as Theatre Passe Muraille, Toronto Workshop Productions, Buddies in Bad Times, and Necessary Angel in his analysis. City Stages combines primary archival research with the scholarly literature emerging from both the humanities and social sciences. The result is a comprehensive and empirical examination of the relationship between the theatrical arts and the urban spaces that house them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268419540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442684195423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442684195.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK